                        "username": "huangalang"
                    },
                    "message": "the main reason this doesnt serve our purpose is this xyz.openbmc_project.Object.Enable default = false , but in our case\nwe will disable a running process or thread , so the default setting should be enable , however you remind of me that if we should use this interface instead \nwe maybe can set xyz.openbmc_project.Object.Enable = true at initial stage for our purpose , what do you think?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 24,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "huangalang",
                        "email": "huang.alang@inventec.com",
                        "username": "huangalang"
                    },
                    "message": "but from the description of this interface , it aims at boot settings related application , not sure it fits in our situation , please share your idea , thanks"
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 24,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Patrick Williams",
                        "email": "patrick@stwcx.xyz",
                        "username": "williamspatrick"
                    },
                    "message": "> the main reason this doesnt serve our purpose is this xyz.openbmc_project.Object.Enable default = false\n\nThis value should have no bearing here.  The \"default\" value of any property is only the one set up in the constructor if the server object doesn't have an alternative.  Essentially this is the uninitialized value.  Any implementation can set the default to something more appropriate.\n\n> but from the description of this interface , it aims at boot settings related application , not sure it fits in our situation , please share your idea , thanks\n\nThe \"aims at boot settings\" isn't really true.  There was simply an example in the interface description.  We put this into Object.Enable so it could be widely applicable.  I think it fits the case you've described in your commit message fine."
                },
